WEBVTT

00:01.734 --> 00:04.700
I don't know about you guys,
but I am ready for a nap.

00:05.567 --> 00:07.233
Me, too. I don't get this.

00:07.300 --> 00:09.300
Isn't lunch supposed to give
you energy?

00:09.367 --> 00:10.800
I miss kindergarten.

00:12.934 --> 00:14.033
Nap time?

00:14.900 --> 00:17.233
What? I thought we were
all on the same page.

00:17.300 --> 00:18.367
[CHUCKLES]

00:19.967 --> 00:21.900
Afternoon, people. [CHUCKLES]

00:22.133 --> 00:24.266
Now that's a meal
that would energize me.

00:26.066 --> 00:27.166
You think so, huh?

00:27.300 --> 00:29.834
But when fast food is all you eat,
your energy kind of evens out.

00:29.900 --> 00:32.300
The only thing you eat is fast food?

00:32.400 --> 00:34.467
Oh, breakfast, lunch and dinner.

00:34.600 --> 00:37.533
-You're my hero.
-Why? Cooking's great.

00:37.633 --> 00:39.633
I'm no good at it, but I wish I was.

00:39.700 --> 00:42.000
I can't even microwave popcorn
without burning it.

00:42.066 --> 00:44.266
So, you never eat
like a home-cooked meal?

00:44.367 --> 00:46.533
When my mom sends me care packages,
I do, yeah.

00:46.667 --> 00:48.400
Mr. Dig, that's just wrong!

00:48.467 --> 00:49.967
You need to take care of yourself.

00:50.033 --> 00:52.033
You need to eat
three proper meals a day

00:52.100 --> 00:53.367
and you need to eat meals that have

00:53.433 --> 00:55.433
all your major
food groups represented.

00:56.133 --> 00:58.033
Uh-oh. Did I just sound
like my mother?

00:58.166 --> 00:59.200
I'm too young for that.

00:59.633 --> 01:02.000
You know, I had a great dinner
at Lizzie's last night.

01:02.100 --> 01:04.467
Your mom makes the best meatloaf.

01:04.900 --> 01:05.900
Meatloaf?

01:06.667 --> 01:08.433
Your mom makes meatloaf?

01:08.867 --> 01:10.734
[CHUCKLING]
That's one of my favorites!

01:10.800 --> 01:12.500
Yeah, Lizzie's Mom's a great cook.

01:12.600 --> 01:14.200
Way better than my mom.

01:15.100 --> 01:17.100
Why do you think we spend
so much time at your house?

01:17.567 --> 01:18.800
Uh, the company?

01:19.834 --> 01:22.533
Compared to the good eats,
the company is secondary.

01:23.233 --> 01:24.266
[SCOFFS]

01:24.333 --> 01:26.133
If I didn't like him so much,

01:26.266 --> 01:27.300
I'd hate him.

01:27.800 --> 01:31.333
Well, Mr. Dig, I'm sure my mom
will not mind cooking dinner for you.

01:31.467 --> 01:32.567
When should I be there?

01:35.233 --> 01:37.600
Did I just invite Mr. Dig to dinner?

01:37.734 --> 01:40.433
But you're not supposed to see
your teachers outside of school!

01:40.734 --> 01:42.600
It's like seeing Santa in blue jeans.

01:42.667 --> 01:44.800
Um, I'll ask my mom
and get back to you.

01:46.300 --> 01:47.667
What? Who said that?

01:47.734 --> 01:49.100
'Cause I know it wasn't me.

01:49.567 --> 01:50.567
[BELL RINGING]

01:50.633 --> 01:52.467
Oh, there's the bell.
Don't want to be late.

01:54.800 --> 01:58.133
-What were you thinking?
-Inviting our teacher to dinner?

01:59.100 --> 02:00.100
[SIGHS]

02:00.367 --> 02:02.100
That's what I'm trying to figure out.

02:02.700 --> 02:04.700
[THEME SONG PLAYING]

02:43.166 --> 02:45.600
Okay, so even though
Mr. Dig is my favorite sub,

02:46.100 --> 02:47.934
I should never have
invited him to dinner.

02:48.066 --> 02:50.667
But since I did, you guys have
to be on your best behavior.

02:50.767 --> 02:51.934
Does that mean I shouldn't sing?

02:52.066 --> 02:53.667
Oh, I love it when he sings.

02:53.834 --> 02:55.200
Since when do you sing, Dad?

02:55.333 --> 02:57.400
Well, rarely, because I'm always
on my best behavior.

02:57.834 --> 02:59.867
Lizzie, don't worry.
We are not that weird.

03:00.000 --> 03:01.700
Well, speaking of weird.

03:02.133 --> 03:06.133
Trust me. I've got too many problems
of my own to be worrying about yours.

03:06.266 --> 03:09.633
Good. That means no burping, belching,
or making funny faces during dinner.

03:09.834 --> 03:13.033
Okay, I can cut back
on the funny faces, but...

03:13.200 --> 03:15.967
I don't always have control
over the burping and...

03:17.166 --> 03:18.166
[BURPS LOUDLY]

03:19.133 --> 03:20.233
...belching.

03:21.233 --> 03:24.400
And I don't always have control over
when I'm going to crush you.

03:24.533 --> 03:26.200
Okay, seriously, Matt. Please.

03:26.266 --> 03:27.934
This is really, really
important to me.

03:28.066 --> 03:29.400
I just want to get through
dinner tonight

03:29.467 --> 03:31.200
as fast and painlessly as possible.

03:31.367 --> 03:34.533
You know, I want to get through
the school year the same way.

03:34.667 --> 03:36.200
Tsk. Guess we're both
out of luck, huh.

03:36.533 --> 03:38.834
-[PHONE RINGING]
-That's Miranda. I'll get it upstairs.

03:39.400 --> 03:40.533
Matt?

03:40.867 --> 03:42.800
-[PHONE RINGING]
-Something wrong at school?

03:42.934 --> 03:44.967
It's my teacher, Ms. Chapman.

03:45.133 --> 03:48.200
You know, she used to be so nice
and friendly,

03:48.333 --> 03:51.533
but now, it's like
she's in a bad mood all the time.

03:51.633 --> 03:55.467
-What do you mean?
-Well, she piles on the homework,

03:55.567 --> 03:58.433
gives us a time out
if we forget to raise our hand.

03:58.867 --> 04:00.700
She made Lanny stay after school

04:00.834 --> 04:03.700
just because he threw away his gum
the wrong way.

04:04.133 --> 04:05.233
What's the right way?

04:05.367 --> 04:08.066
It's supposed to be neatly folded
in a gum wrapper

04:08.166 --> 04:10.133
or a tissue or something.

04:10.233 --> 04:12.367
Otherwise, it just sits there...

04:13.600 --> 04:16.033
...bald, shriveled,

04:17.400 --> 04:19.166
staring at you.

04:21.700 --> 04:22.967
At least, that's what she says.

04:23.500 --> 04:24.500
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

04:24.633 --> 04:27.233
You just hang in there, son.
Maybe her bad mood will go away.

04:27.300 --> 04:28.567
Women are funny that way.

04:29.266 --> 04:31.633
-Hey!
-What? Aren't you?

04:32.200 --> 04:33.600
-Yeah.
-See?

04:34.367 --> 04:37.734
Just keep the conversation moving.
You don't want any lulls.

04:38.033 --> 04:39.200
They can be dangerous.

04:39.333 --> 04:42.367
Yeah. Awkward pauses
make people say really stupid things

04:42.467 --> 04:43.967
they wouldn't ordinarily say.

04:44.100 --> 04:45.967
[CHUCKLES] Okay, so no lulls.

04:46.100 --> 04:49.000
And don't let your parents show him
any of your baby pictures.

04:49.100 --> 04:50.934
Oh, and don't let him see your room.

04:51.100 --> 04:53.900
And whatever you do,
don't let him out of your sight.

04:54.033 --> 04:56.467
If left alone with anyone
in your family,

04:56.600 --> 04:59.567
they can reveal your deepest,
darkest secrets.

04:59.700 --> 05:02.100
I don't have any deep, dark secrets.

05:02.233 --> 05:03.734
At least none that they know about.

05:04.200 --> 05:05.967
Okay, this is not helping, you guys.

05:06.100 --> 05:07.600
This situation is beyond help.

05:07.734 --> 05:09.500
Yeah, you're pretty much doomed.

05:10.800 --> 05:13.433
Note to self:
Get two new best friends.

05:17.033 --> 05:19.867
Okay. He should be here,
like, any minute.

05:21.567 --> 05:23.166
[SNICKERS]

05:23.333 --> 05:24.400
[MATT LAUGHS]

05:24.500 --> 05:26.100
What? Do I have something in my teeth?

05:26.734 --> 05:28.667
No. Not your teeth.

05:29.900 --> 05:31.533
Mom, can you do something about him?

05:32.133 --> 05:34.467
-Matt.
-I didn't do anything!

05:34.600 --> 05:36.133
Now, let's keep it that way.

05:36.300 --> 05:39.100
You know, honey,
this stuff is really good.

05:39.266 --> 05:41.767
-Dad!
-Honey, accidents happen.

05:41.900 --> 05:43.300
-Here, let me help you.
-Yeah?

05:43.433 --> 05:44.633
-Come on.
-All right.

05:47.500 --> 05:49.066
-[JO SCREAMS]
-SAM: Hey, hey!

05:54.100 --> 05:55.867
-JO: Ouch! [SCREAMS]
-SAM: I got it. I got it.

05:56.500 --> 05:57.967
Get away from me!

05:58.033 --> 05:59.100
-I got it.
-[JO GASPS]

06:00.200 --> 06:01.300
-Okay.
-[SIGHS]

06:01.433 --> 06:02.700
[DOORBELL RINGS]

06:02.834 --> 06:03.834
You want to get that?

06:03.900 --> 06:04.900
[SIGHS IN EXASPERATION]

06:06.033 --> 06:07.667
Oh, this can't be happening.

06:12.333 --> 06:13.734
[WATER DRIPPING]

06:14.967 --> 06:16.133
-Hello.
-Hello.

06:16.233 --> 06:17.700
Um...

06:17.934 --> 06:19.367
I brought pecan pie.

06:19.533 --> 06:20.834
Pecan pie?

06:20.967 --> 06:24.300
I love pecan pie.
It's one of my favorites.

06:24.400 --> 06:27.333
Mine, too, but maybe I should have
brought towels and a stain remover.

06:27.400 --> 06:28.734
[LAUGHING]

06:28.934 --> 06:29.967
Yeah.

06:30.033 --> 06:33.500
Come on in. I'm Jo.
This is my husband, Sam.

06:33.633 --> 06:35.633
-Hi.
-Our son, Matt,

06:35.734 --> 06:37.200
-and of course, you know Lizzie.
-[CHUCKLES]

06:37.367 --> 06:38.867
Digby Sellers. Pleased to meet you.

06:40.033 --> 06:41.500
Digby Sellers?

06:41.633 --> 06:43.800
No. You're Mr. Dig.

06:43.967 --> 06:45.200
Mr. Dig!

06:45.533 --> 06:47.133
Lizzie, nice to see you.

06:48.667 --> 06:51.000
You've got a little something
stuck to your shoe there.

06:51.066 --> 06:52.967
-[MATT LAUGHS]
-I do?

06:53.533 --> 06:55.333
-[ALL CHUCKLING]
-[LIZZIE CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY]

06:55.467 --> 06:56.600
I do.

06:56.734 --> 06:58.567
Is it time for him to go yet?

06:59.200 --> 07:01.800
So, listen, we can get cleaned up,
but maybe,

07:01.934 --> 07:04.400
Matt, you can take Mr. Sellers around,
show him the house?

07:04.533 --> 07:06.900
Please, please.
Please call me "Digby."

07:07.200 --> 07:08.467
-Digby?
-Okay.

07:09.734 --> 07:11.600
And you can call me mortified.

07:13.400 --> 07:16.567
Okay, Digby.
Let's start with Lizzie's room.

07:17.800 --> 07:18.800
[CHUCKLES]

07:20.166 --> 07:21.166
[SIGHS]

07:22.200 --> 07:24.000
He had a tour of your house?

07:24.100 --> 07:27.667
We did, and trust me, Gordo, it was
totally disastrous in the beginning.

07:30.233 --> 07:33.333
Then having Digby at my house
wasn't so bad after all.

07:33.400 --> 07:34.600
Who is Digby?

07:35.166 --> 07:37.934
Wait, did you just call
Mr. Dig "Digby"?

07:38.767 --> 07:40.033
That's so wrong.

07:40.166 --> 07:43.100
Gordo, I told you. It was not
as bad as I thought it would be.

07:43.233 --> 07:45.834
Plus, my parents were totally normal
for a change.

07:51.467 --> 07:54.500
And he and my dad formed this bond
over some old rock band

07:54.600 --> 07:55.800
that I'd never heard of before.

07:59.266 --> 08:02.734
Uh-oh, music can be a pretty
strong connection.

08:02.867 --> 08:04.467
Lifelong friendships can be formed

08:04.600 --> 08:06.467
just because two people
like the same song.

08:06.600 --> 08:08.633
Gordo, it was just something
they had in common.

08:08.767 --> 08:11.667
It's not like my dad and Mr. Dig
are going to become friends now.

08:11.967 --> 08:13.533
Then, what's your dad doing here?

08:13.600 --> 08:14.600
Huh?

08:17.834 --> 08:20.166
That's a question
definitely worth repeating.

08:20.233 --> 08:22.800
Dad, what... What are you doing here?

08:22.934 --> 08:24.967
Lizzie, I am really glad I found you.

08:25.100 --> 08:26.934
-Dad, is something wrong?
-Not at all.

08:27.000 --> 08:28.500
But you and Mom
never come to my school

08:28.600 --> 08:30.066
unless I accidentally
left my lunch at home

08:30.166 --> 08:32.367
and that hasn't happened since,
like, fourth grade!

08:32.533 --> 08:34.900
No, I... I was going crazy
looking for this CD

08:35.000 --> 08:36.800
that Digby and I were
talking about last night.

08:36.900 --> 08:37.967
And guess what?

08:38.033 --> 08:40.567
I found it.
It was wedged right in my car seat.

08:41.033 --> 08:44.934
How cool! Now, don't you have
somewhere to be? Like work?

08:45.066 --> 08:47.367
Not really. I really need
to find Digby, though,

08:47.467 --> 08:48.834
because I think
he'd like to hear this.

08:49.567 --> 08:51.500
And I'd kinda
like to hear you leaving.

08:51.900 --> 08:54.600
Um, why don't you try
the teacher's lounge? It's that way.

08:54.734 --> 08:55.867
Thank you, David.

08:56.333 --> 08:59.400
Oh, Lizzie, by the way,
I am so glad you introduced us,

08:59.567 --> 09:00.834
'cause he's really a cool guy.

09:00.900 --> 09:02.233
Yeah, sure, Dad. Oh, my...

09:02.367 --> 09:05.100
What? That is the worst thing
I've ever heard.

09:05.533 --> 09:07.767
See you at home. Hey, Digby!

09:09.333 --> 09:11.800
The planets must be misaligned
or something.

09:11.867 --> 09:14.400
Mr. Dig's at your house,
your father is here.

09:15.033 --> 09:16.166
It's not normal.

09:18.166 --> 09:21.600
What can I say?
Gordo is totally right, as usual.

09:23.900 --> 09:28.300
Okay, there is no way Ms. Chapman
can be mean to me today.

09:28.834 --> 09:30.100
I am wearing green.

09:30.767 --> 09:32.033
Green is supposed to make people...

09:32.100 --> 09:33.734
[BREATHES HEAVILY] ...happy.

09:41.433 --> 09:44.033
Why didn't anyone send me that memo?

09:46.100 --> 09:47.200
What does red mean?

09:48.333 --> 09:50.900
[GASPS] Okay.
You're on your own, Matt.

09:56.266 --> 09:57.500
Morning, class.

09:58.934 --> 10:01.900
Please take everything off your desks,
except for a piece of paper

10:01.967 --> 10:04.400
and write your names
in the upper right-hand corner.

10:10.133 --> 10:12.200
Melina. Melina, hey!

10:12.734 --> 10:15.567
Can I borrow a pen?
Mine kind of ran out of...

10:21.767 --> 10:22.967
[CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY]

10:23.600 --> 10:24.767
Hello.

10:25.367 --> 10:28.433
Is this the way we behave
during a pop quiz, Matthew?

10:28.567 --> 10:31.300
By talking and disturbing
your neighbors?

10:31.367 --> 10:35.000
[CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY]
I was just hoping to borrow a pen,

10:35.133 --> 10:37.734
'cause, you see, mine ran out of ink.

10:37.800 --> 10:38.900
-[MATT SCRIBBLES]
-Oh, Matthew.

10:38.967 --> 10:42.000
Matthew, Matthew, Matthew.

10:42.166 --> 10:44.300
Please call me "Matt."

10:45.000 --> 10:46.633
Well, Matt.

10:46.800 --> 10:50.233
I hate to do this,
but, due to your lack of preparation

10:50.400 --> 10:51.700
and responsibility,

10:51.834 --> 10:56.233
you've turned our pop spelling quiz
into a pop vocabulary quiz.

10:56.367 --> 10:57.967
[ALL GROANING]

10:59.100 --> 11:01.166
Is this a zoo or a classroom?

11:02.033 --> 11:04.100
[CHUCKLES] That's what I thought.

11:04.233 --> 11:07.834
Now, your first word
is "responsibility."

11:08.033 --> 11:11.066
Spell it correctly
and write it in a sentence.

11:15.900 --> 11:18.166
Miranda, you were so right
about the facial thing.

11:18.300 --> 11:20.567
I feel so much better
about my dad and Mr. Dig.

11:20.700 --> 11:22.500
In fact, I even feel like it's okay.

11:22.633 --> 11:26.867
Excellent. Now, while the mask
is drying and tightening your pores,

11:27.000 --> 11:28.600
<i>now is a good time to eat.</i>

11:29.133 --> 11:31.166
-Ice cream is good.
-Why ice cream?

11:31.600 --> 11:33.734
I don't know, but it sounds good,
though, doesn't it?

11:33.834 --> 11:36.266
Hey! Whatever you're eating in there,
save some for me.

11:39.066 --> 11:41.133
[BOTH SCREAMING]

11:41.200 --> 11:42.900
[SCREAMING]

11:44.233 --> 11:46.667
-Oh, Hi, Lizzie.
-Miranda, I'll call you back.

11:46.867 --> 11:47.900
Yeah, please.

11:48.100 --> 11:50.166
Mr. Dig, what are you doing here?

11:51.033 --> 11:53.200
Hey, Digby, hurry up.
The game's gonna start.

11:53.667 --> 11:55.166
Lizzie, you got some
gunk on your face.

11:55.333 --> 11:56.700
As if I don't know!

11:57.266 --> 11:58.767
I'm cleaning my pores!

11:59.033 --> 12:00.266
Good night, honey.

12:01.266 --> 12:02.567
Have fun cleaning, Lizzie.

12:02.700 --> 12:04.567
[GASPS AND GRUNTS]

12:06.200 --> 12:09.567
That's it! My father and my teacher
cannot be friends anymore,

12:09.700 --> 12:11.233
interfering in my life.

12:17.200 --> 12:20.700
I can't believe Ms. Chapman
didn't make me wear a hat today.

12:20.900 --> 12:23.500
You weren't late,
you weren't unprepared

12:23.600 --> 12:27.000
and you didn't talk
without raising your hand first.

12:27.133 --> 12:30.000
Hmm. I must be having an off day.

12:30.133 --> 12:32.967
I don't know how I'm going
to make it through the school year.

12:33.066 --> 12:36.500
I know. I mean,
the homework alone is torture.

12:37.367 --> 12:39.300
I asked my mom
the other night for help,

12:39.467 --> 12:42.700
but she said she didn't learn calculus
till college!

12:42.867 --> 12:44.433
Hey, you know what
Clark Benson told me?

12:44.533 --> 12:46.200
-What?
-That Ms. Chapman

12:46.333 --> 12:48.266
gets to school at 6:00 a.m.

12:48.367 --> 12:51.333
And then she leaves, like, really,
really late at night every single day!

12:51.467 --> 12:53.633
What does she do here for so long?

12:53.800 --> 12:57.166
That's easy. She figures out new ways
to make our lives miserable.

12:57.233 --> 13:00.633
-She needs a hobby.
-What she needs is a life.

13:00.700 --> 13:02.033
Or at least more friends.

13:02.133 --> 13:03.433
-Mmm.
-Hmm.

13:06.200 --> 13:09.467
Actually, that's not a bad idea.

13:12.734 --> 13:14.667
Man, have these birds
got it made or what?

13:14.734 --> 13:17.500
Oh, you're telling me? They're getting
room and board for free!

13:17.633 --> 13:18.867
[BOTH LAUGHING]

13:20.033 --> 13:22.100
No! It's not fair.

13:22.200 --> 13:24.400
Mr. Dig got home
from school before I did.

13:24.533 --> 13:27.166
That's it. I am for
Operation Break-Up.

13:28.300 --> 13:29.600
Hey, do you want a soda or something?

13:29.834 --> 13:31.266
Hey, you've got your hands full.
I'll get it.

13:32.667 --> 13:33.900
Miss McGuire.

13:34.333 --> 13:35.500
Shouldn't you be doing your homework?

13:37.266 --> 13:41.000
And to add more fuel to my fire,
I don't need a homework monitor.

13:41.066 --> 13:42.033
Oof!

13:42.667 --> 13:44.233
I'm just joking!

13:44.800 --> 13:45.967
You want a soda?

13:46.433 --> 13:49.433
Hey, it's my soda to offer. Not yours.

13:50.133 --> 13:51.467
No, thanks.

13:53.233 --> 13:54.400
-Hey, Dad.
-Hey, Lizzie.

13:54.533 --> 13:56.500
Check out this bird house
Digby and I are making.

13:56.633 --> 13:59.333
-Pretty sweet, huh?
-Mm-hmm. All you need is cable now.

14:01.600 --> 14:02.667
So, Dad,

14:02.800 --> 14:05.133
you and Digby have been spending
a lot of time together.

14:05.200 --> 14:07.633
Yeah, I know.
He is so much fun to hang out with.

14:08.667 --> 14:10.767
Well, don't you ever miss
doing stuff by yourself?

14:10.867 --> 14:11.934
-Like what?
-You know,

14:12.033 --> 14:14.300
like painting those lawn gnomes
that you like so much,

14:14.367 --> 14:17.500
or doing crossword puzzles
or roller disco.

14:17.600 --> 14:19.400
-Roller disco?
-Yeah.

14:19.533 --> 14:21.734
I saw those pictures of you and Mom
when you first met.

14:24.200 --> 14:25.300
[CHUCKLES]

14:25.367 --> 14:27.834
Honey, that was a real long time ago.

14:28.767 --> 14:30.266
What about those two friends of yours?

14:30.367 --> 14:32.600
You know, the ones
that have that chimp?

14:32.667 --> 14:34.300
I haven't seen them around in a while.

14:34.433 --> 14:37.533
Oh, Jeremy and David?
They're off on vacation with Fredo.

14:37.834 --> 14:39.433
Here we go. Cool and refreshing.

14:39.900 --> 14:41.100
Hey, you staying for dinner?

14:42.266 --> 14:44.233
Please say "no." Please say "no."

14:44.900 --> 14:46.767
You know how much
I love Jo's meatloaf.

14:46.867 --> 14:47.967
-Yeah.
-[DIGBY LAUGHS]

14:48.000 --> 14:50.867
Oh, too bad. I think
we're ordering in pizza,

14:50.967 --> 14:53.533
and I know how sick
you are of fast food, so,

14:53.667 --> 14:55.533
I wouldn't blame you
if you didn't want to stay.

14:55.633 --> 14:58.033
You know, actually I haven't had
a pizza in about a week.

14:58.800 --> 15:00.900
-Slap on a few anchovies. I'm in.
-Hey.

15:06.400 --> 15:09.133
Mom, can I talk
to you about some stuff?

15:09.233 --> 15:11.367
Sure, sweetie.
What's going on with you?

15:11.500 --> 15:13.667
You were so quiet
at dinner last night.

15:14.100 --> 15:15.900
Well, it's hard to get
a word in edgewise

15:15.967 --> 15:17.567
when Dad and Mr. Dig get started.

15:20.900 --> 15:23.333
It's nice to see your dad
make a new friend though, isn't it?

15:24.600 --> 15:25.700
Not really.

15:26.333 --> 15:29.433
Actually, [SIGHS] that's what
I wanted to talk to you about.

15:29.633 --> 15:32.500
I mean, I like Mr. Dig, a lot,

15:32.633 --> 15:35.200
and I'm really glad that
he and Dad like each other,

15:35.367 --> 15:37.066
but, sometimes...

15:39.533 --> 15:41.767
Sometimes I just wish
that they weren't friends.

15:42.066 --> 15:43.800
Oh, my gosh.

15:43.934 --> 15:46.467
I can't believe
it didn't occur to me earlier.

15:46.600 --> 15:48.834
This must be awkward for you.

15:48.900 --> 15:51.934
I guess, I just thought because
you like Mr. Dig so much yourself...

15:52.066 --> 15:53.300
And I do like him.

15:53.367 --> 15:54.400
He's your favorite substitute teacher,

15:54.467 --> 15:56.533
and I know I've heard you say
how cool you think he is.

15:56.667 --> 15:58.633
And he is cool, Mom, but I just...

15:59.533 --> 16:02.000
It was all so clear
before we started talking.

16:02.100 --> 16:04.567
You know what?
I'm gonna talk to your dad.

16:05.033 --> 16:07.800
Because our home
should be your sanctuary.

16:08.100 --> 16:09.100
Yeah.

16:09.233 --> 16:12.166
A place for all of us, all our friends
to feel very comfortable.

16:14.667 --> 16:15.934
Our friends?

16:17.033 --> 16:19.400
[SIGHS] Then I guess that means
Dad's friends, too.

16:21.600 --> 16:23.734
Even if he is my substitute teacher.

16:23.867 --> 16:25.533
I mean, you guys are okay

16:25.600 --> 16:27.934
when Gordo and Miranda
come over here all the time.

16:28.100 --> 16:29.800
Do you still want me to talk to Dad?

16:31.700 --> 16:33.767
The only thing
harder than asking Mom for help,

16:33.900 --> 16:36.100
is accepting that
Dad and Mr. Dig are friends.

16:37.300 --> 16:38.767
I hate being so mature.

16:40.533 --> 16:42.233
I'm not sure what I want right now.

16:42.433 --> 16:44.900
[SMACKS LIPS] Well, you want me
to give you a ride to school

16:44.967 --> 16:46.066
on my way to the market?

16:46.200 --> 16:48.600
Your brother has invited
his teacher over for dinner tonight.

16:48.734 --> 16:50.066
What? Why?

16:50.667 --> 16:51.767
I don't know.

16:52.000 --> 16:54.967
Well, just as long as he knows
what he's getting himself into.

16:55.033 --> 16:56.033
[CHUCKLES]

17:00.500 --> 17:04.467
Now remember, be nice to her,
compliment her, laugh at her jokes.

17:04.600 --> 17:08.166
Matt, come on. If tonight is anything

17:08.233 --> 17:10.200
like the night when we met Mr. Dig,

17:10.300 --> 17:11.700
you have nothing to worry about.

17:11.767 --> 17:12.767
[DOORBELL RINGING]

17:13.533 --> 17:14.533
It's probably her.

17:14.633 --> 17:17.633
Somebody answer it before
she has time to write a tardy slip.

17:17.767 --> 17:18.800
Quickly!

17:19.166 --> 17:20.233
I'll go.

17:20.367 --> 17:21.467
-Sam?
-Yeah.

17:21.600 --> 17:23.066
You've got something
on your tie again.

17:23.133 --> 17:25.500
Oh... sorry, honey.

17:26.734 --> 17:27.734
[SMACKS LIPS]

17:27.800 --> 17:30.333
Matt, you know,
having your teacher over

17:30.400 --> 17:32.433
for dinner could be dangerous.

17:32.567 --> 17:35.433
But I want Mom and Ms. Chapman

17:35.500 --> 17:37.834
to be friends like
Dad and your teacher.

17:38.300 --> 17:39.667
No, you don't.

17:39.767 --> 17:41.800
Yes, yes, I do.

17:43.734 --> 17:45.467
He's young. He'll learn.

17:46.433 --> 17:47.734
[JO LAUGHS LOUDLY]

17:50.767 --> 17:52.667
My husband's always joking.

17:53.533 --> 17:55.500
I wouldn't know.
I don't have a husband.

17:57.934 --> 18:00.500
Thank you for coming to my house
for dinner, Ms. Chapman.

18:00.734 --> 18:02.066
You're welcome, Matthew.

18:02.133 --> 18:03.133
[CHUCKLES]

18:03.600 --> 18:05.300
[LAUGHING] Matthew?

18:05.500 --> 18:08.867
Um, I'm Matthew's
older sister, Lizzie.

18:09.000 --> 18:10.100
Hello, Lizzie.

18:11.166 --> 18:12.300
Uh...

18:15.633 --> 18:17.066
Okay, here's a lull.

18:17.200 --> 18:18.700
Gordo and Miranda said to avoid them

18:18.834 --> 18:20.834
because someone might say
something embarrassing.

18:21.300 --> 18:24.166
Matthew didn't stop sucking his thumb
until he was, like, five.

18:25.500 --> 18:27.233
[CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY] My sister,

18:27.300 --> 18:30.333
she takes after my dad
in the joke department.

18:31.834 --> 18:33.000
Not very funny.

18:33.967 --> 18:36.867
Well, I hope you're hungry.
We've got a ton of food.

18:37.033 --> 18:39.000
I've got steak, potatoes...

18:39.133 --> 18:41.767
Oh, I don't eat meat, or carbs.

18:42.967 --> 18:45.600
Oh. Well, we've got lots of salad.

18:45.767 --> 18:46.967
Is there dressing?

18:49.734 --> 18:51.834
Yes. A vinaigrette. I make it myself.

18:51.967 --> 18:53.166
I prefer it dry.

18:55.166 --> 18:58.333
Well, I'll just make you
a new one then.

18:58.567 --> 18:59.567
[SOFTLY] Ow!

19:00.033 --> 19:01.033
[DOORBELL RINGS]

19:02.300 --> 19:03.433
I'll get that.

19:03.567 --> 19:05.467
Any excuse to get out of the room.

19:09.100 --> 19:11.233
So, you're a teacher?

19:11.834 --> 19:13.500
I'm friends with a teacher.

19:13.667 --> 19:15.600
Actually, he's a substitute teacher.

19:15.734 --> 19:17.433
Yeah, my sub, Mr. Dig.

19:17.567 --> 19:18.867
Digby, actually.

19:19.333 --> 19:21.066
Digby? What Digby?

19:21.200 --> 19:22.834
Digby Sellers. You know him?

19:23.066 --> 19:26.467
Yes! Well, no. It's been years.

19:27.000 --> 19:28.900
He's the reason
why I went into teaching.

19:29.033 --> 19:32.233
He had such enthusiasm,
such knowledge.

19:32.767 --> 19:34.000
Do you see him often?

19:34.200 --> 19:36.200
Please tell him I said "hello."

19:36.734 --> 19:38.000
Tell him yourself.

19:42.767 --> 19:44.200
It is you!

19:44.700 --> 19:45.900
Jasmine!

19:46.600 --> 19:47.834
Jasmine?

19:48.200 --> 19:50.500
It's been a long time.

19:51.200 --> 19:52.433
Too long!

19:52.967 --> 19:56.700
I just came by to see my friend Sam

19:56.834 --> 19:59.200
and give him back his CD.

20:01.233 --> 20:02.667
Um...

20:03.100 --> 20:04.767
Brought a copy of track three.
It rocks.

20:04.900 --> 20:05.967
Cool.

20:06.667 --> 20:07.767
Digby?

20:09.934 --> 20:11.233
Yes, Jasmine?

20:11.867 --> 20:14.433
I'm suddenly starving.

20:14.500 --> 20:17.567
Well, that dry salad
will just take a minute to make.

20:18.700 --> 20:20.800
-How does Chinese sound?
-Perfect.

20:20.934 --> 20:23.000
-That is, if you don't mind.
-Not at all.

20:23.133 --> 20:24.367
Hey, I thought we were
going to stay up

20:24.433 --> 20:26.100
and watch sports highlights later.

20:26.233 --> 20:28.300
Let him go, Sam. Let him go.

20:28.433 --> 20:29.900
Matt?

20:30.633 --> 20:32.200
[CHUCKLES NERVOUSLY] Yeah?

20:32.767 --> 20:34.834
Don't worry about that extra homework.

20:35.000 --> 20:38.066
I have a feeling
I won't have time to grade it.

20:38.266 --> 20:39.266
Excellent.

20:40.734 --> 20:42.033
Thank you for having me over.

20:42.166 --> 20:45.834
Your home... No,
your entire family is just lovely.

20:46.533 --> 20:47.567
Lovely!

20:49.066 --> 20:50.233
Shall we?

20:50.333 --> 20:51.834
[GIGGLING]

20:54.767 --> 20:55.934
[GIGGLING]

20:57.467 --> 20:59.300
Okay, what just happened here?

20:59.433 --> 21:01.934
I don't know, but I think it was good.

21:02.100 --> 21:03.400
Really good.

21:03.567 --> 21:05.433
I got to go call Lanny.

21:05.567 --> 21:09.567
And tell him
Ms. Chapman has a first name.

21:10.567 --> 21:11.600
[CHUCKLES]

21:12.800 --> 21:14.900
So, should I still talk to your dad?

21:17.300 --> 21:19.266
Hey there, little gnome.

21:22.400 --> 21:23.467
[BOTH LAUGHING]

21:24.900 --> 21:27.967
On second thought, maybe
some of Dad's friends aren't so bad.

21:33.433 --> 21:34.533
MALE CREW MEMBER: Test.

21:34.633 --> 21:36.266
Well, this is our son, Matt,

21:36.500 --> 21:37.800
[LAUGHING]
and of course, you know Lizzie.

21:37.867 --> 21:39.000
-Matt. Yeah.
-MALE CREW MEMBER: Cut!

21:39.066 --> 21:40.667
Where am I supposed to be looking?

21:40.767 --> 21:42.233
You need to eat a... [GRUNTS]

21:42.700 --> 21:43.834
You need...

21:43.967 --> 21:45.033
Yeah.

21:45.567 --> 21:47.700
-[OBJECTS CLATTERING]
-[LAUGHS]

21:47.834 --> 21:49.533
Did... something wrong?

21:49.667 --> 21:50.767
-What is it?
-What is it?

21:51.266 --> 21:52.500
-[BANGS]
-Ah!

21:53.967 --> 21:55.800
And the only answers
I can come up with

21:55.867 --> 21:58.266
is just to break
Mr. Dad and my Dig up.

21:58.400 --> 22:00.800
[CREW LAUGHING]

22:01.867 --> 22:03.834
[THEME MUSIC PLAYING]
